 Principle of Object Orientation
 
 Object Orientation is the prospective of looking at the real world as a collection of object.
 E.g -> pen,book,laptop,bottle 
 
 No object in entire World is useless.Every object is in constant interaction with others objects.No object is perfectly isolated.
 E.g -> laptop-charger
 
 Each object belongs to a particular type which is known as class although their type class does'nt exists in real world . But object of this 
 do exist in real world. Each object has something , every object does something. What all object has is known as properties, attribute, state. what all does 
 is known as behaviour of object or action performed by an object.
 a.Data type / data member
 b.method /  member function
 
 TO create an object in java, the JVM must be invoked. This is done with the help of new keyword, such object which we want to use in future or we wanr to use
 multiple times, must be assigned to a reference. However if we want to create an object which we would use only once. For such object we don't need to provide 
 any reference. This object for which no reference is assigned are also known as anonymous object.
 
 
 7.Why does a computer or memory devices understand only zeroes and ones?
 
 ->Computers use zeroes and ones (binary) because their fundamental components, like transistors, work as simple electrical switches that are either 
 ON (1) or OFF (0), representing the presence or absence of voltage; this binary system is the most reliable and efficient way to represent data and
 instructions at the hardware level, making complex tasks possible through combinations of these two states. 
 
 
A variable is a name assigned for a memory location inorder to efficiently store or retrieve data. 

Data type - mechanism provided in programming languag which helps in converting real world data to binary form.

Java inbuilt data type
1.byte - 8 bit
2.short - 2 byte
3.long - 8 byte
4.int  - 4 byte
5.float - 4 byte
6.char  - 2 byte
7.boolean - 1 byte


8. Why does Java provides us with 4 different data types to store real world data? 
-> If we try to exceed the maximum range of a data type , we may encounter an overflow error and if we try to store value less than minimum range of a data type,
 we encounter an underflow error. Java provides four different primitive data types for storing whole numbers (byte, short, int, and long) and two for fractional 
 (floating-point) numbers (float and double) to allow programmers to optimize memory usage and performance based on the specific range and precision requirements
  of the data.
  
  
9. How are integers stored in memory?
-> Integers are converted into binary form using base 2 format.


TYPE CASTING
Type casting refers to the process of storing one data type into variable of another data type.

types:
1.implicit - process of storing a value of smaller data types into  variable of bigger data type. Such conversions are internal , automatically performed by 
the compiler. Hence this process is also known as implicit type casting or type conversion.

2.explicit - when we try to store the value of bigger data type into a variable of smaller data types. such conversions are not allowed by the compiler 
automatically. Hence we as programmers must externally instruct the compiler to perform the conversion. This type of conversion is also known as explicit type 
casting. The major drawback of explicit type casting is that there might be loss in accuracy of data.
 
 Type casting Chart
 byte -> short -> int  ->  float -> double
                  ^   \     /
                  |     long  
                  char   
                          
                       
10. why do we need to add a suffix f and l for storing values inside float variable & long variable?
 
 
 *  Whenever there is an expression involving multiple data type , the result will always have biggest data type.
E.g -> double r = 5 + 10.5 + 10.5f


Primitive Data type & their default values
a.byte - 0
b.short -0
c.int   -0
d.long  -0l
e.float -0.0f
f.double -0.0
g.char  - \u0000
h.boolean - false

11. Is Java a pure object oriented programming language?
-> Java is not pure object oriented because of its supports the primitive data type.


Segment of JRE

1.code segment
2.static segment
3.stack segment
4.Heap segment

ARRAYS

-> if we want to store data in java , we can use the following approaches:
a. variable approach
b. Array approach

If we want to store data in java , we can use the variable approach but if we have to store data in large amount the variable approach is not efficient.
In such cases we should go for arrays approach. Arrays are data structures which can be used to store similar type of data. In java , Arrays are treated as objects and 
hence they alloted memory on the heap segment. 

